<feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><title>A Pelican Blog - physics</title><link href="https://til.grayvines.com/" rel="alternate"></link><link href="https://til.grayvines.com/feeds/physics.atom.xml" rel="self"></link><id>https://til.grayvines.com/</id><updated>2020-05-25T13:59:09-04:00</updated><entry><title>Liquid Magnets</title><link href="https://til.grayvines.com/liquid-magnets.html" rel="alternate"></link><published>2020-05-25T13:59:09-04:00</published><updated>2020-05-25T13:59:09-04:00</updated><author><name></name></author><id>tag:til.grayvines.com,2020-05-25:/liquid-magnets.html</id><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;There aren't really any liquid magnets.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curie_temperature"&gt;Curie temperature&lt;/a&gt; of a material is the
temperature above which it loses its magnetic properties.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Even &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferrofluid"&gt;ferrofluids&lt;/a&gt; are not
actually liquid magnets, they're small solid magnets suspended in a
liquid (oil).&lt;/p&gt;
